{"title_page": "Chris Simmons", "text_new": "{{for|the racing driver|Chris Simmons (racing driver)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Chris Simmons\n| image                 = Chris Simmons.jpg\n| imagesize             =\n| caption               =\n| birth_name            = Christopher Matthew Simmons\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1975|1|8}}\n| birth_place           = [[Gravesend, Kent]], [[England]]\n| death_date            =  <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} Death date then birth -->\n| death_place           =\n| othername             =\n| occupation            = Actor\n| years_active          =\n| spouse                =\n| domesticpartner       =\n| website               =\n| footnotes             =\n}}\n'''Christopher Matthew Simmons''' (born 8 January 1975 in [[Gravesend, Kent]]) is an English television and stage actor. He is best known for his roles as DC [[Mickey Webb]] in ''[[The Bill]]'', Mark Garland in ''[[EastEnders]]'' and Stuart Summer in ''[[Hollyoaks]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nSimmons grew up on Singlewell Road in Gravesend and attended Saint Georges CofE Secondary School.<ref name=\"Gravesend Reporter\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gravesendreporter.co.uk/news/tv_cop_unveils_youth_initiative_1_600571|title=TV cop unveils youth initiative|date=24 June 2010|work=Gravesend Reporter|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref> Prior to taking up acting, he had several jobs including working as a diver on the [[River Thames]] with his Dad.<ref>[http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/9926752.Stars_set_to_shine_in_panto/ Stars set to shine in panto (From Echo)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Simmons is a supporter of [[Gillingham F.C.]]{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}. He trained as an actor at London Academy of Performing Arts.\n\n==Career==\nSimmons' first television appearance was on the 1998 ITV series ''Desperately Seeking Stardom'', in which a group of unemployed actors went to [[Hollywood]] to try to find acting roles.<ref name=\"Desperately Seeking Stardom\">{{cite web | url=http://www.talktalk.co.uk/tv-guide/person/cjymq/chris-simmons | title=Chris Simmons | work=[[TalkTalk Group]] | accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/television-review-desperately-seeking-stardom-1092303.html# Television Review: Desperately Seeking Stardom - Arts and Entertainment - The Independent<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nSimmons found fame as DC [[Mickey Webb]] in ''[[The Bill]]'' from 2000 to 2003 (having previously appeared playing different roles in 1998 and 1999). He made guest appearances over the interim including the live episode in 2003 before returning as a regular in 2005 until the series ended in 2010.  He also guest starred in ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''<ref>[http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/w4tsv/casualty--series-27---39-garage-flowers Casualty | Series 27 - 39. Garage Flowers | Radio Times<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]''.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b053cty3/credits BBC One - Doctors, Series 16, When the Heart Breaks - Credits<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn October 2011 he appeared in ''[[EastEnders]]'' as [[Mark Garland]], a love interest for [[Kat Moon]], for a few episodes.<ref name=\"Metro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/tv/877749-eastenders-kat-moon-tempted-to-cheat-on-alfie-with-new-character-mark|title=EastEnders' Kat Moon tempted to cheat on Alfie with new character Mark | work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers]]|accessdate=16 October 2011|location=London}}</ref>\nHe has since made a guest appearance in the Tracy Beaker spin-off CBBC show, '[[The Dumping Ground]]': In episode 8 of series 1 (1x08), entitled 'Dreamland' he played the father to [[List of Tracy Beaker series characters#Rick Barber|Rick Barber]], Gerry.\n\nSimmons was a patron for the CPC Kent charity until it closed in 2014.<ref name=\"CPC Kent\">{{cite news | url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/news/devastated-as-charity-closes-after-12847/ | title=Devastated as Medway children's charity CPC Kent closes after 30 years | work=Kent Online | date=17 February 2014 | accessdate=8 February 2015 | author=Cox, Lynn}}</ref>  He ran the [[London Marathon]] in 2009,<ref name=\"2009 marathon winners\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/mobile/entertainment/8019816.stm | title=A night of surprises at TV gala | work=[[BBC]] | date=26 April 2009 | accessdate=8 February 2015 | author=Osborn, David}}</ref> and again in 2014.<ref name=\"Marathon 2014\">{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/london-marathon/10760362/London-Marathon-2014-celebrity-runners.html | title=London Marathon 2014 celebrity runners | work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | date=11 April 2014 | accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref>  In 2013 he took part in the [[Bupa Great Birmingham Run]].<ref name=\"Birmingham Marathon\">{{cite news | url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/celebrities-join-great-birmingham-run-6205141 | title=Stars of sport, stage and screen taking part in Bupa Great Birmingham Run | work=Birmingham Mail | date=18 October 2013 | accessdate=8 February 2015 | author=Bentley, David}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he was part of a cast of ''The Wizard of Oz'' [[pantomime]] at Swallows Leisure Centre, in [[Sittingbourne]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The complete guide to the brightest, brashest pantos across Kent |url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/whats-on/news/the-complete-guide-to-the-46368/ |accessdate=13 February 2019 |work=Kent Online |date=13 November 2015 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe also currently works on a youth initiative in his hometown of Gravesend.<ref name=\"Gravesend Reporter\" />\n\nIn 2019 he was cast as Stuart Sumner in ''[[Hollyoaks]]''.<ref name=\"Digital Spy\">{{cite news | url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/hollyoaks/a26422288/hollyoaks-brand-new-character-chris-simmons-stuart-sumner-the-bill/ | title=I'm delighted to join the cast of Hollyoaks | work=Digital Spy | date=20 February 2019 | accessdate=12 March 2019 | last=Warner|first= Sam}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, he was interviewed alongside his ''[[The Bill]]'' co-star [[Sally Rogers]] for a [https://www.patreon.com/thebillpodcast three-part The Bill Podcast] to promote Chris starring in Sally's play The Still Room.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0799709}}\n* [http://www.thebill.com/videos/videodetail/item_200038.htm Chris Simmons interview at ''The Bill'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141218185816/http://wayneandabel.co.uk/ Chris Simmons comedy sketch show ''Wayne and Abel'']\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simmons, Chris}}\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gravesend, Kent]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Kent]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the racing driver|Chris Simmons (racing driver)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                  = Chris Simmons\n| image                 = Chris Simmons.jpg\n| imagesize             =\n| caption               =\n| birth_name            = Christopher Matthew Simmons\n| birth_date            = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1975|1|8}}\n| birth_place           = [[Gravesend, Kent]], [[England]]\n| death_date            =  <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} Death date then birth -->\n| death_place           =\n| othername             =\n| occupation            = Actor\n| years_active          =\n| spouse                =\n| domesticpartner       =\n| website               =\n| footnotes             =\n}}\n'''Christopher Matthew Simmons''' (born 8 January 1975 in [[Gravesend, Kent]]) is an English television and stage actor. He is best known for his roles as DC [[Mickey Webb]] in ''[[The Bill]]'', Mark Garland in ''[[EastEnders]]'' and Stuart Summer in ''[[Hollyoaks]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nSimmons grew up on Singlewell Road in Gravesend and attended Saint Georges CofE Secondary School.<ref name=\"Gravesend Reporter\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gravesendreporter.co.uk/news/tv_cop_unveils_youth_initiative_1_600571|title=TV cop unveils youth initiative|date=24 June 2010|work=Gravesend Reporter|accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref> Prior to taking up acting, he had several jobs including working as a diver on the [[River Thames]] with his Dad.<ref>[http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/9926752.Stars_set_to_shine_in_panto/ Stars set to shine in panto (From Echo)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Simmons is a supporter of [[Gillingham F.C.]]{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}. He trained as an actor at London Academy of Performing Arts.\n\n==Career==\nSimmons' first television appearance was on the 1998 ITV series ''Desperately Seeking Stardom'', in which a group of unemployed actors went to [[Hollywood]] to try to find acting roles.<ref name=\"Desperately Seeking Stardom\">{{cite web | url=http://www.talktalk.co.uk/tv-guide/person/cjymq/chris-simmons | title=Chris Simmons | work=[[TalkTalk Group]] | accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/television-review-desperately-seeking-stardom-1092303.html# Television Review: Desperately Seeking Stardom - Arts and Entertainment - The Independent<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nSimmons found fame as DC [[Mickey Webb]] in ''[[The Bill]]'' from 2000 to 2003 (having previously appeared playing different roles in 1998 and 1999). He made guest appearances over the interim including the live episode in 2003 before returning as a regular in 2005 until the series ended in 2010.  He also guest starred in ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''<ref>[http://www.radiotimes.com/episode/w4tsv/casualty--series-27---39-garage-flowers Casualty | Series 27 - 39. Garage Flowers | Radio Times<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]''.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b053cty3/credits BBC One - Doctors, Series 16, When the Heart Breaks - Credits<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn October 2011 he appeared in ''[[EastEnders]]'' as [[Mark Garland]], a love interest for [[Kat Moon]], for a few episodes.<ref name=\"Metro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/tv/877749-eastenders-kat-moon-tempted-to-cheat-on-alfie-with-new-character-mark|title=EastEnders' Kat Moon tempted to cheat on Alfie with new character Mark | work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers]]|accessdate=16 October 2011|location=London}}</ref>\nHe has since made a guest appearance in the Tracy Beaker spin-off CBBC show, '[[The Dumping Ground]]': In episode 8 of series 1 (1x08), entitled 'Dreamland' he played the father to [[List of Tracy Beaker series characters#Rick Barber|Rick Barber]], Gerry.\n\nSimmons was a patron for the CPC Kent charity until it closed in 2014.<ref name=\"CPC Kent\">{{cite news | url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/news/devastated-as-charity-closes-after-12847/ | title=Devastated as Medway children's charity CPC Kent closes after 30 years | work=Kent Online | date=17 February 2014 | accessdate=8 February 2015 | author=Cox, Lynn}}</ref>  He ran the [[London Marathon]] in 2009,<ref name=\"2009 marathon winners\">{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/mobile/entertainment/8019816.stm | title=A night of surprises at TV gala | work=[[BBC]] | date=26 April 2009 | accessdate=8 February 2015 | author=Osborn, David}}</ref> and again in 2014.<ref name=\"Marathon 2014\">{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/london-marathon/10760362/London-Marathon-2014-celebrity-runners.html | title=London Marathon 2014 celebrity runners | work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | date=11 April 2014 | accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref>  In 2013 he took part in the [[Bupa Great Birmingham Run]].<ref name=\"Birmingham Marathon\">{{cite news | url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/celebrities-join-great-birmingham-run-6205141 | title=Stars of sport, stage and screen taking part in Bupa Great Birmingham Run | work=Birmingham Mail | date=18 October 2013 | accessdate=8 February 2015 | author=Bentley, David}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he was part of a cast of ''The Wizard of Oz'' [[pantomime]] at Swallows Leisure Centre, in [[Sittingbourne]].<ref>{{cite news |title=The complete guide to the brightest, brashest pantos across Kent |url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/whats-on/news/the-complete-guide-to-the-46368/ |accessdate=13 February 2019 |work=Kent Online |date=13 November 2015 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe also currently works on a youth initiative in his hometown of Gravesend.<ref name=\"Gravesend Reporter\" />\n\nIn 2019 he was cast as Stuart Sumner in ''[[Hollyoaks]]''.<ref name=\"Digital Spy\">{{cite news | url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/hollyoaks/a26422288/hollyoaks-brand-new-character-chris-simmons-stuart-sumner-the-bill/ | title=I'm delighted to join the cast of Hollyoaks | work=Digital Spy | date=20 February 2019 | accessdate=12 March 2019 | last=Warner|first= Sam}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, he was interviewed alongside his ''[[The Bill]]'' co-star [[Sally Rogers]] for a [https://www.patreon.com/thebillpodcast three-part The Bill Podcast] to promote Chris starring in Sally's play The Still Room.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0799709}}\n* [http://www.thebill.com/videos/videodetail/item_200038.htm Chris Simmons interview at ''The Bill'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141218185816/http://wayneandabel.co.uk/ Chris Simmons comedy sketch show ''Wayne and Abel'']\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simmons, Chris}}\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\